  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here I experimented with the hidden layer number, hidden layer size, number of iterations, and the learning rate. The first attempt is the default settings, in which a consistent around 80-85% prediction is reached with the sample point, as well as a seemingly constant 1.0 accuracy score.\n",
    "\n",
    "I then lowered the size of the hidden layers but increased the number, doing 3 layers of 5 instead of 1 layer of 100. This greatly reduced the accuracy of the output, leading to extremely inconsistent accuracy scores ranging from 0.4 to 0.8.\n",
    "\n",
    "Finally, I kept the layers at 3x5 and increased the iterations from 200 to 600 and multiplied the learning rate by 10 to make it 0.01. This led to the best results with a consistent 1.0 accuracy score and sample point prediction percentages in the high 90s. There was only one run in which these rates dipped down and ended up with a 0.7 accuracy score."
   ]
