   "source": [
    "# Part 7: Conclusions and takeaways\n",
    "\n",
    "In your own words describe the results of the notebook. Which model(s) performed the best on the dataset? Why do you think that is? Did anything surprise you about the exercise?\\\n",
    "\\\n",
    "Most of the models in this dataset performed very consistently high, with all but one of the neural networkk trainings getting reasonably consistent 1.0 accuracy scores. However, there is one standout in terms of prediction percentages which is the k-Nearest Neighbors that is predicting the correct category on the sample data with 100% accuracy. The other models, including the neural network with the right parameters, can get that percentage into the 90s, but k nearest is the most accurate on the chosen sample.\\\n",
    "\\\n",
    "I believe k-Nearest performed best due to the way species are separated. When differentiating between species you look at metrics such as the ones provided in the features of this dataset, and species have similar metrics in these categories. Therefore, when looking at a point and determining a species, the metrics around it is a very good place to look. Species categorization is much more relative than predictive which is why an unsupervised model works the best.\\\n",
    "\\\n",
    "The only surprise for me is how consistently well all the models did over this data. It makes sense as it is a commonly used learning set, but it is interesting to see a consistently high performance all around."
   ]
  }
